00:13:22,333 --> 00:13:23,833
these are great questions

284
00:13:23,875 --> 00:13:26,583
and they bring us to the practical side of non self

285
00:13:27,250 --> 00:13:30,125
the common misconception is that without a self

286
00:13:30,500 --> 00:13:32,416
you just sit around doing nothing

287
00:13:32,458 --> 00:13:35,250
or float aimlessly through life with no direction

288
00:13:35,500 --> 00:13:37,416
but that's not at all what happens

289
00:13:37,875 --> 00:13:40,000
as the Zen master Linji put it

290
00:13:45,500 --> 00:13:46,291
the profound

291
00:13:46,291 --> 00:13:48,375
simplicity of this teaching points to action

292
00:13:48,375 --> 00:13:50,875
without the complication of a self centered narrative

293
00:13:51,416 --> 00:13:54,291
the difference is in the who that's doing the action

294
00:13:54,458 --> 00:13:57,875
or more accurately the absence of a who

295
00:13:58,833 --> 00:13:59,208
so

296
00:13:59,208 --> 00:14:01,375
what does this actually look like on a Tuesday morning

297
00:14:01,375 --> 00:14:02,708
when you're stuck in traffic

298
00:14:03,083 --> 00:14:04,458
your life continues

299
00:14:04,625 --> 00:14:06,666
but without that extra layer of 'me-ness'

300
00:14:06,666 --> 00:14:09,791
clogging everything up decisions still happen

301
00:14:09,916 --> 00:14:12,250
but they arise from wisdom and conditions rather

302
00:14:12,250 --> 00:14:13,625
than ego preferences

303
00:14:14,333 --> 00:14:16,125
responsibilities are still fulfilled

304
00:14:16,500 --> 00:14:17,916
often more effectively

305
00:14:18,333 --> 00:14:21,166
because there's no self centered resistance to them

306
00:14:21,875 --> 00:14:23,333
goals can still be pursued

307
00:14:23,333 --> 00:14:25,708
but without the desperate attachment to outcomes

308
00:14:26,375 --> 00:14:27,375
the Buddha himself

309
00:14:27,583 --> 00:14:30,083
was incredibly active after his Enlightenment

310
00:14:30,500 --> 00:14:34,583
teaching for 45 years establishing a monastic order

311
00:14:34,791 --> 00:14:36,333
traveling extensively

312
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:39,916
clearly function doesn't stop when self dissolves

313
00:14:40,375 --> 00:14:43,000
neuroscience gives us interesting insights here too

314
00:14:43,041 --> 00:14:43,750
studies show that

315
00:14:43,750 --> 00:14:45,875
when experienced meditators perform tasks

316
00:14:45,875 --> 00:14:47,375
from a state of non self

317
00:14:47,541 --> 00:14:49,500
their performance often improves

318
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:51,541
there's less second guessing

319
00:14:51,583 --> 00:14:53,708
less performance anxiety

320
00:14:53,708 --> 00:14:56,250
and more direct engagement with the task at hand

321
00:14:56,875 --> 00:14:58,541
think about athletes in the zone

322
00:14:58,541 --> 00:15:00,958
or musicians who become one with their instrument

323
00:15:01,416 --> 00:15:02,791
they're functioning at their peak

324
00:15:02,791 --> 00:15:05,125
precisely when the self steps out of the way

325
00:15:06,291 --> 00:15:08,875
as the legendary basketball coach Phil Jackson

326
00:15:08,875 --> 00:15:12,333
who incorporated Zen teachings into his coaching said

327
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:22,583
but what about morality if there's no me

328
00:15:22,875 --> 00:15:24,833
what prevents harmful actions

329
00:15:25,458 --> 00:15:28,000
this is where many people misunderstand non self

330
00:15:28,208 --> 00:15:31,083
the realization of non self doesn't eliminate ethics

331
00:15:31,166 --> 00:15:32,625
it transforms them

332
00:15:32,833 --> 00:15:35,125
when you don't see yourself as separate from others

333
00:15:35,416 --> 00:15:38,041
causing harm makes less and less sense

334
00:15:38,875 --> 00:15:41,000
compassionate action emerges naturally

335
00:15:41,041 --> 00:15:42,666
not because you should be good

336
00:15:42,666 --> 00:15:45,083
but because you directly experience others suffering

337
00:15:45,083 --> 00:15:46,708
as not separate from your own

338
00:15:47,666 --> 00:15:49,375
The 8th century Buddhist master

339
00:15:49,375 --> 00:15:50,916
Shantideva put it beautifully

340
00:16:02,041 --> 00:16:03,583
so in practical terms

341
00:16:03,625 --> 00:16:07,125
living from non self might look like working diligently

342
00:16:07,250 --> 00:16:09,958
but without identifying as the hard working one

343
00:16:09,958 --> 00:16:13,541
loving deeply but without possessiveness or need

344
00:16:13,875 --> 00:16:17,625
creating art or music but without needing recognition

345
00:16:17,750 --> 00:16:18,875
helping others

346
00:16:19,291 --> 00:16:21,250
without seeing them as separate from yourself

347
00:16:22,375 --> 00:16:24,583
it's not that personality disappears

348
00:16:24,583 --> 00:16:26,458
it's more that you hold it lightly

349
00:16:26,625 --> 00:16:27,500
like a costume

350
00:16:27,500 --> 00:16:29,625
you can wear wholeheartedly without forgetting

351
00:16:29,625 --> 00:16:30,916
you can take it off

352
00:16:31,291 --> 00:16:34,625
you see your personality in the mirror of everyday life

353
00:16:34,791 --> 00:16:36,750
but you no longer mistake the reflection

354
00:16:36,750 --> 00:16:38,000
for who's doing the looking

355
00:16:38,541 --> 00:16:39,583
you wear your identity

356
00:16:39,583 --> 00:16:41,583
like an interesting mask at a party

357
00:16:41,875 --> 00:16:43,708
fully engaged in the character

358
00:16:43,791 --> 00:16:46,375
but secretly smiling at the game of it all

359
00:16:48,458 --> 00:16:51,583
okay so we can still function without a solid me

360
00:16:51,666 --> 00:16:54,166
great but the Buddha wasn't teaching this

361
00:16:54,166 --> 00:16:56,500
just so we could be more effective at our jobs

362
00:16:56,666 --> 00:16:58,708
he was pointing to something much bigger

363
00:17:03,541 --> 00:17:05,875
we've talked about glimpses of non self

364
00:17:05,958 --> 00:17:09,500
the freedom it brings how it transforms relationships

365
00:17:09,500 --> 00:17:11,125
and how it works practically

366
00:17:11,708 --> 00:17:13,958
but now let's explore what the Buddha considered

367
00:17:13,958 --> 00:17:15,875
the ultimate purpose of this teaching

368
00:17:16,166 --> 00:17:17,625
complete liberation

369
00:17:18,791 --> 00:17:21,208
the Buddha didn't teach non self as an interesting

370
00:17:21,208 --> 00:17:24,166
philosophical concept he taught it as medicine

371
00:17:24,500 --> 00:17:27,041
for the fundamental disease of human existence

372
00:17:27,625 --> 00:17:28,458
suffering

373
00:17:29,000 --> 00:17:31,750
he recognized that at the root of all our suffering

374
00:17:31,833 --> 00:17:33,958
lies this mistaken belief in a separate

375
00:17:33,958 --> 00:17:35,166
permanent self

376
00:17:35,375 --> 00:17:38,000
and when this illusion is completely seen through

377
00:17:38,291 --> 00:17:39,958
something profound happens

378
00:17:40,958 --> 00:17:42,416
in Buddhist terminology

379
00:17:42,416 --> 00:17:44,875
this complete liberation is called Nirvana

380
00:17:45,375 --> 00:17:46,208
literally meaning

381
00:17:46,208 --> 00:17:49,458
blowing out like a flame being extinguished

382
00:17:50,208 --> 00:17:52,416
but what's being extinguished isn't you

383
00:17:52,916 --> 00:17:55,000
it's the illusion of a separate self

384
00:17:55,208 --> 00:17:55,708
it's like

385
00:17:55,708 --> 00:17:57,500
you've been wearing noise cancelling headphones

386
00:17:57,500 --> 00:18:00,166
your entire life and suddenly they're removed

387
00:18:00,333 --> 00:18:02,625
the world explodes into symphonic clarity

388
00:18:02,625 --> 00:18:03,875
that was always there

389
00:18:04,458 --> 00:18:06,250
as the Buddha said

390
00:18:14,708 --> 00:18:16,166
so what actually changes

391
00:18:16,166 --> 00:18:18,000
when this ultimate liberation occurs

392
00:18:18,458 --> 00:18:20,041
first fear

393
00:18:20,250 --> 00:18:23,500
especially fear of death dramatically transforms

394
00:18:24,125 --> 00:18:25,416
when you deeply realize

395
00:18:25,416 --> 00:18:28,375
there was never a permanent you to begin with

396
00:18:28,375 --> 00:18:32,541
the terror of losing this you naturally subsides

397
00:18:33,166 --> 00:18:34,625
death is still respected

398
00:18:35,791 --> 00:18:38,708
but it's seen more as a transition than an end

399
00:18:39,666 --> 00:18:41,333
the Tibetan Buddhist master

400
00:18:41,333 --> 00:18:43,541
Dilgo Khyentse Rinpoche explained

401
00:18:57,416 --> 00:18:58,208
second

402
00:18:58,250 --> 00:19:00,875
suffering takes on a completely different quality

403
00:19:01,458 --> 00:19:03,416
the Buddha never claimed that physical pain

404
00:19:03,416 --> 00:19:05,000
would disappear with enlightenment

405
00:19:05,541 --> 00:19:07,791
but he did teach that the mental suffering

406
00:19:07,791 --> 00:19:10,166
we add to our experience the resistance

407
00:19:10,166 --> 00:19:11,958
the aversion the craving

408
00:19:11,958 --> 00:19:13,208
can completely cease

409
00:19:14,166 --> 00:19:16,333
imagine experiencing life's challenges

