who integrates Buddhist thinking with psychology

415
00:19:26,791 --> 00:19:29,750
describes it as the freedom to be nobody

416
00:19:30,375 --> 00:19:32,000
there's an incredible lightness

417
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:34,916
in not having to be somebody special all the time

418
00:19:36,666 --> 00:19:39,166
third a natural joy emerges

419
00:19:39,500 --> 00:19:42,500
not the excited grasping happiness we usually chase

420
00:19:42,708 --> 00:19:45,541
but a profound contentment that's always available

421
00:19:45,666 --> 00:19:48,125
regardless of external circumstances

422
00:19:49,166 --> 00:19:51,500
the Thai Forest master Ajahn Chah

423
00:19:51,500 --> 00:19:54,541
called it the peace that comes from letting go

424
00:19:55,458 --> 00:19:58,083
fourth perception itself fundamentally shifts

425
00:19:58,208 --> 00:19:59,791
the world doesn't change

426
00:19:59,958 --> 00:20:03,000
but how you experience it transforms completely

427
00:20:03,458 --> 00:20:05,708
instead of seeing separate objects and people

428
00:20:05,791 --> 00:20:07,833
you directly perceive the interconnected

429
00:20:07,833 --> 00:20:08,791
nature of everything

430
00:20:09,375 --> 00:20:12,000
boundaries become permeable fluid

431
00:20:12,166 --> 00:20:13,791
more like convenient designations

432
00:20:13,791 --> 00:20:15,125
than ultimate realities

433
00:20:16,250 --> 00:20:17,791
the contemporary teacher

434
00:20:17,791 --> 00:20:21,500
Adyashanti describes it as the end of your world

435
00:20:21,708 --> 00:20:23,916
not in an apocalyptic sense

436
00:20:24,250 --> 00:20:26,000
but in the sense that the world

437
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:28,750
as you've constructed it falls away

438
00:20:29,083 --> 00:20:31,041
revealing what was always here

439
00:20:31,875 --> 00:20:34,750
but perhaps the most significant shift is this

440
00:20:34,916 --> 00:20:36,833
the seeking finally stops

441
00:20:37,083 --> 00:20:39,583
the constant feeling that something is missing

442
00:20:40,041 --> 00:20:42,208
that you need to become something more

443
00:20:42,625 --> 00:20:44,958
that fulfillment is around the next corner

444
00:20:45,083 --> 00:20:49,041
comes to an end as the ancient Chan master Linji said

445
00:21:08,041 --> 00:21:10,708
this doesn't mean you become passive or complacent

446
00:21:11,083 --> 00:21:14,250
quite the opposite without the self centered filters

447
00:21:14,416 --> 00:21:16,500
you're able to respond to life directly

448
00:21:16,666 --> 00:21:18,958
spontaneously compassionately

449
00:21:19,416 --> 00:21:21,375
without the hesitation and confusion that

450
00:21:21,375 --> 00:21:22,916
comes from self concern

451
00:21:23,541 --> 00:21:25,500
so what does all this mean for you

452
00:21:25,500 --> 00:21:27,041
watching this right now

453
00:21:27,625 --> 00:21:29,125
it means that this freedom

454
00:21:29,125 --> 00:21:30,083
this peace

455
00:21:30,083 --> 00:21:33,541
this clarity isn't something distant or theoretical

456
00:21:33,583 --> 00:21:36,666
it's your birthright it's what you already are

457
00:21:36,708 --> 00:21:39,916
when the illusion of a separate self falls away

458
00:21:40,666 --> 00:21:42,916
as the Buddha said in his final teaching

459
00:21:46,416 --> 00:21:49,416
so now let's wrap this all up with a mystery

460
00:21:49,416 --> 00:21:50,833
that might just change everything

461
00:21:55,875 --> 00:21:58,625
so we've explored what happens when you don't exist

462
00:21:59,041 --> 00:22:01,125
we've seen how the self is more like a process

463
00:22:01,125 --> 00:22:02,000
than a thing

464
00:22:02,333 --> 00:22:04,500
how freedom emerges when this illusion is seen

465
00:22:04,500 --> 00:22:07,208
through how relationships transform

466
00:22:07,625 --> 00:22:09,416
how we can function practically

467
00:22:09,791 --> 00:22:12,333
and the ultimate liberation this points toward

468
00:22:12,916 --> 00:22:15,625
but here's the cosmic joke that the Buddha discovered

469
00:22:15,625 --> 00:22:16,916
under the Bodhi Tree

470
00:22:17,583 --> 00:22:19,750
the self spends its entire existence

471
00:22:19,750 --> 00:22:20,708
desperately trying to

472
00:22:20,708 --> 00:22:23,083
protect itself from something that never happens

473
00:22:23,458 --> 00:22:25,625
because that self never truly existed

474
00:22:25,625 --> 00:22:26,916
in the first place

475
00:22:27,583 --> 00:22:28,791
it's like spending your life

476
00:22:28,791 --> 00:22:30,541
afraid of monsters under the bed

477
00:22:30,541 --> 00:22:33,791
and then one day finally looking underneath

478
00:22:34,541 --> 00:22:37,208
only to discover there was never anything there

479
00:22:37,916 --> 00:22:40,041
this leaves us with a profound mystery

480
00:22:40,041 --> 00:22:41,875
if you're not who you think you are

481
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:44,083
then what's really living this life

482
00:22:44,833 --> 00:22:46,250
if you're not your thoughts

483
00:22:46,541 --> 00:22:48,583
they come and go while awareness remains

484
00:22:49,000 --> 00:22:50,541
if you're not your emotions

485
00:22:51,000 --> 00:22:53,500
they change constantly while awareness watches

486
00:22:53,875 --> 00:22:55,375
if you're not your body

487
00:22:55,666 --> 00:22:58,125
every cell is replaced over time

488
00:22:58,541 --> 00:23:00,500
if you're not your memories or life story

489
00:23:00,500 --> 00:23:01,875
which change and fade

490
00:23:02,500 --> 00:23:06,291
then what are you the answer can't be put into words

491
00:23:06,416 --> 00:23:08,708
because words and concepts are tools of the thinking

492
00:23:08,708 --> 00:23:11,916
mind and this mystery lies beyond thinking

493
00:23:12,458 --> 00:23:15,250
it can only be discovered through direct experience

494
00:23:15,583 --> 00:23:16,208
by looking

495
00:23:16,208 --> 00:23:18,125
deeply into the nature of your own awareness

496
00:23:18,833 --> 00:23:20,958
as the great Zen master Huineng said

497
00:23:24,125 --> 00:23:27,375
this isn't nihilism it's not saying nothing exists

498
00:23:27,583 --> 00:23:29,583
it's pointing to a profound reality

499
00:23:29,583 --> 00:23:31,416
beyond our conceptual frameworks

500
00:23:31,833 --> 00:23:34,000
beyond the stories we tell about ourselves

501
00:23:34,375 --> 00:23:37,125
the invitation of Buddhism isn't to believe in non

502
00:23:37,125 --> 00:23:38,416
self as a concept

503
00:23:38,708 --> 00:23:41,875
but to investigate your direct experience right now

504
00:23:42,500 --> 00:23:44,666
to look deeply into this sense of I

505
00:23:44,666 --> 00:23:46,333
and see what's really there

506
00:23:47,125 --> 00:23:49,958
the Zen tradition calls this the great death

507
00:23:50,250 --> 00:23:51,791
not the death of the body

508
00:23:52,083 --> 00:23:54,708
but the death of the illusion of a separate self

509
00:23:55,125 --> 00:23:57,500
and what's discovered through this great death

510
00:23:57,625 --> 00:23:59,250
is what some traditions call

511
00:23:59,250 --> 00:24:02,875
your original face what you were before you were born

512
00:24:03,416 --> 00:24:04,458
what you've always been

513
00:24:04,458 --> 00:24:06,875
beneath the costumes and masks of identity

514
00:24:08,791 --> 00:24:10,958
I invite you to get curious about this

515
00:24:10,958 --> 00:24:11,916
to wonder

516
00:24:12,041 --> 00:24:17,125
to investigate not intellectually but experientially

517
00:24:18,375 --> 00:24:20,166
what if you didn't have to wait for enlightenment

518
00:24:20,166 --> 00:24:21,541
to experience freedom

519
00:24:22,083 --> 00:24:24,000
what if you could taste it right now

520
00:24:24,333 --> 00:24:27,458
by simply pausing and noticing that awareness

521
00:24:27,458 --> 00:24:30,541
which is already present already complete

522
00:24:30,916 --> 00:24:33,916
already free of a separate self

523
00:24:34,916 --> 00:24:37,250
because when the illusion of you falls away

524
00:24:37,250 --> 00:24:39,750
you stop surviving and start being

525
00:24:40,208 --> 00:24:42,333
you stop performing and start living

526
00:24:42,583 --> 00:24:45,500
as the contemporary teacher Rupert Spira puts it

527
00:24:51,250 --> 00:24:53,625
I invite you to sit quietly for a moment

528
00:24:53,791 --> 00:24:56,250
close your eyes if you're comfortable doing so

529
00:24:56,500 --> 00:24:57,500
and simply notice

530
00:24:57,500 --> 00:25:00,250
who or what is aware of your current experience

531
00:25:00,750 --> 00:25:02,291
not what you're aware of

532
00:25:02,458 --> 00:25:05,000
but what is this awareness itself

533
00:25:06,375 --> 00:25:07,833
and I'll leave you with that question

534
00:25:07,833 --> 00:25:09,500
to explore in your own time

535
00:25:09,583 --> 00:25:11,125
because that exploration

536
00:25:11,291 --> 00:25:13,125
is the heart of the Buddhist path

